  "prompt": "Is there a \"blind trust\" provision for American Presidents, and how is it enforced?",
  "response": "While there is no explicit legal requirement for presidents to place their assets in a blind trust, modern presidents typically work to avoid conflicts of interest by divesting investments or transferring management to independent trustees. The primary guidelines are:\n\n1. Ethics in Government Act and conflict of interest laws provide general framework\n2. Office of Government Ethics (OGE) provides recommendations\n3. Presidents historically have voluntarily taken steps to separate personal finances from official duties\n\nNotable practices include:\n- Selling stocks/investments\n- Creating financial management arrangements\n- Disclosing financial interests annually\n- Recusing from decisions with direct personal financial implications\n\nHowever, enforcement is somewhat limited, relying more on political and public pressure than strict legal penalties. The president is not legally compelled to completely divest or create a true \"blind trust\" in the strictest sense.\n\nSome presidents, like Jimmy Carter, have gone to extraordinary lengths to avoid conflicts, while others have been more relaxed about financial separation.\n\nThe 2017 STOCK Act also increased transparency requirements for federal officials regarding financial transactions and potential conflicts of interest.\n\nWhile guidelines exist, the system ultimately depends significantly on the individual president's commitment to ethical standards and public transparency.",
